Nuchal thickening with a septated cystic hygroma is commonly associated with Turner syndrome, which is caused by a missing or partially missing X chromosome. One of the typical physical features of Turner syndrome is congenital lymphedema, or swelling, of the hands and feet. Anal atresia, port-wine stain, and microphthalmia are not typically associated with Turner syndrome.
